    Effects of Acid on Bone.
Additionally, there is net proton influx into the mineral with release of bone sodium and potassium. During chronic metabolic acidosis, there is also inhibition of osteoblast activity, resulting in reduced bone formation, and an increase in osteoclast activity, resulting in increased bone resorption and release of calcium and anionic proton buffers. These physicochemical and cell-mediated bone responses to metabolic acidosis, in addition to an acidosis induced increased urine calcium excretion, without a corresponding increase in intestinal calcium absorption, induce a net loss of body calcium which is almost certainly derived from the mineral stores of bone.
